		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [2.70]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Tassoth&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>oh one other thing which in my experience makes someone a better player, is to try out as many classes as you can. I currently have a main of a 56 beastlord, which (excuse modesty) i play extremely well, and i've had peeps and high level guilds say to me. <br><br>But on top of that i have a bard, warrior and soon to be cleric twinks. Some people may find it pointless, especially since none of them are high lvl. But the reason i play these classes is to learn the limitations and skills that they get so i can better understand the group dynamic. If you IMO go into a group and now exactly what a bard, cleric, warrior or Beastlord in my case can do then it makes you a better player and more likely for you to fit in and do your job; either that little bit better or makes you able to fit in that little bit easier.&nbsp;&nbsp;And in my experience that is extremely usefull and important in both the Bard and Beastlords case, since these are the rarest or least grouped class in the game (also in my experience).<br><br>So in conclussion, play whatever you want, but extra knowledge is always helpfull to both you and future groups.<br><br>Good luck hope that helps</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br /><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=481000" target="akztarg">The Iksar</a><br><br><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=595504" target="akztarg">Madho</a><br><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1120614" target="akztarg">Novocane</a><br><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.ht